To summarize how well the proposed model detects seizure events while controlling the rate of false alarm events per hour of EEG, we plot an event-level Free Receiver Operating Characteristic curve (FROC) (Fig. 3). While Fig. 2 shows how well the model ranks seizure vs. non-seizure windows, Fig. 3 shows how that ranking becomes clinically meaningful alarm events per hour after post-processing, which cannot be inferred from window-level ROC/PR because overlapping windows and event merging fundamentally change the relationship between false-positive windows and false alarm events. Moving along the curve corresponds to changing the operating threshold: lowering the threshold increases sensitivity (more events detected) but also increases FA/h, whereas raising it reduces false alarms at the cost of missed events. The annotated point at \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
