				\begin{document}$$\:\tau\:$$\end{document}=0.44 indicates our selected trade-off (0.68 false alarms/hour while detecting 75% of seizure events). The “knee” region around this point suggests achieving higher sensitivity requires a disproportionately large increase in false alarms, supporting our choice of operating point.

The preprocessing pipeline standardizes sampling rate, montage, units, and frequency content before windowing and labelling. Each recording is resampled to a uniform sampling frequency of 200 Hz, ensuring consistent temporal resolution. To obtain a standardized spatial representation, we transformed the original referenced channels into a fixed-order longitudinal bipolar montage. We defined 18 bipolar derivations: Left temporal chain: FP1-F7, F7-T3, T3-T5, T5-O1; Right temporal chain: FP2-F8, F8-T4, T4-T6, T6-O2; Left parasagittal chain: FP1-F3, F3-C3, C3-P3, P3-O1; and Right parasagittal chain: FP2-F4, F4-C4, C4-P4, P4-O2. This yields a matrix of shape \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
